The purpose of the Surveillance and Evaluation Component is to:
Collect, analyze, and monitor data relating to:
Targeted cancers;
As determined by the Department, nontargeted cancers; and
Cancer prevention, education, screening, and treatment programs in the State;
Measure and evaluate the results of the Program, including the results of each component of the Program;
Conduct the Baseline Cancer Study, as provided under subsections (c) and (d) of this section; and
Conduct a Biennial Cancer Study, as provided under § 13-1104 of this subtitle.

The Baseline Cancer Study shall measure:
The number and percentage of individuals who have each targeted cancer, both statewide and in each county;
The number and percentage of individuals within each minority population who have each targeted cancer, both statewide and in each county;
The mortality rate for each targeted cancer, both statewide and in each county;
The mortality rate for different minority populations for each targeted cancer, both statewide and in each county;
The number of identifiable cancers with a high incidence in the State for which there are effective methods of:
Early detection; and
Prevention and treatment after detection;
Any aspect of targeted and nontargeted cancers that the Department seeks to measure; and
Any other factor that the Department determines to be important for measuring rates of cancers in the State or for evaluating whether the Program meets its objectives.
